@translation labeled en project
@(1) Speak to my king, @lab{2}saying (the words) of Aradmu, your servant: 

@(3 = 8) You commanded me, @lab{3}while I was on an expedition to Subir, @lab{4}to firmly secure the taxes on the frontier territory, @lab{5}to thoroughly investigate the state of (this) frontier, @lab{6–7}to confer (with the elites of Subir) about Apilaša, the high commissioner, and have them come to agreement, @lab{8}@i{so that he could bring to them (i.e., the Subir elites) up-to-date instructions}.^1^

@note ^1^  Alternative translation: so that as part of the daily instructions he could bring them (the people of Subir) good news.


@(9) When I stood at the gate of the (local) palace, @lab{10}no one inquired about my king’s well-being, @lab{11}no one rose from (his) seat for me, nor did anyone prostrate himself (before me); @lab{12}this (all) made me very worried.

@(13) But when I drew nearer, @lab{14–16}(I discovered that Apilaša) was dwelling in a @i{portable structure} constructed by means of finely combed fleece (panels stretched between) staked poles inlaid with gold, silver, carnelian, and lapis-lazuli covering an area of thirty sar (ca. 1080 sq. m.). @lab{17}He was all decked out in precious stones and metals. @lab{18}He sat on a throne on a dais placed over a fine carpet,^2^ @lab{19}and had set his feet on a golden footstool. @lab{20}He would not remove his feet in my presence! @lab{21}He had stationed no less than five thousand of his @i{choice} guards to his right and left. @lab{22}(He ordered) six grass-fed oxen and sixty fattened sheep placed (on tables) for a meal; @lab{23}and he took over the performance of my king’s cleansing rites. @lab{24}No one bothered to bring me in through the very gate at which no-one had inquired about your (well-being).

@note ^2^  Alternative translation: under an awning.

@(25 - 30) As I entered (anyway), @lab{26}someone brought me a chair with red gold encrusted knobs and told me: “Sit!” @lab{27}I answered him: “When I am on my king’s orders I stand—I do not sit!” @lab{28}Someone placed^3^ two grass-fed oxen and twenty grass-fed sheep onto my table, @lab{29}but even though I had given no offense, my king’s (own) guardsmen overturned my table. @lab{30}I was so frightened that my skin crawled!

@note ^3^  Var.: heaped up.

@(31 - 32) My king, you gave me orders the evening of the fifth day of the Ninazu Festival Month;

@(33 - 34) I am sending you a courier the evening of the first day of the Swan-Eating Month. @lab{35}It is midday, and war is brewing! @lab{36}Now my king is informed (about all of this)!

