@end B

@translation labeled en project

@(1) Speak to my king, @lab{2}saying (the words) of Aradmu, your servant:

@(3) (Concerning) everything that my king commanded me (to do): @lab{4}(The entire kingdom), from the sea of Dilmun land @lab{5}to the brackish waters at the foot of the Amorite Highlands, @lab{6}to the borders of Simurum in the land of Subir—@lab{7–9}I have inspected the various cities, their (surrounding) territories, their fields and agricultural tracts, and their levees and irrigation ditches; I have imprisoned (all) fugitives.^4^ @lab{10}All the cities obedient to my king @lab{11}... @lab{12}I strengthened the garrisons on their walls; @lab{13}I made their troops submit (to you). @lab{14}... @lab{15}I have drained flooded tracts @lab{16}and had earth work done on @i{dissipated} plots that had been abandoned. @lab{17}... in the fields, and canebrakes in the marshes ... @lab{18–19}Wherever the drawing of water was not sufficient (to irrigate gardens), I had ... pour water by means of buckets. @lab{20–22}(too fragmentary for translation).

#note: ^4^  Alternative translation: @i{I have established a lookout for any leaks}.

@h1 Part B

@(B  1’) On the irrigated desert they set it in watercourses, they wash in the watercourses. 

@(B  2’) Even rustlers and robbers break up the earth (for cultivation) on the (wind)-swept desert.^5^ @lab{3’}As for their men and women, their men go wherever they wish, @lab{4’}and their women hold spindles and needless, wandering on whatever roads they wish. @lab{5’}They set up animal pens in the far-flung desert, @lab{6’}and after pitching their tents and encampments,^6^ @lab{7’}their laborers and tenant farmers then spend their days (working) in the fields. 

#note: ^5^  Alternative translation: I have made rustlers and robbers break up the earth (for cultivation) on the wind-swept steppe.

#note: ^6^  Var.: They rest safely in their tents and encampments.

@(B  8’) I have not neglected the orders of Šulgi, my king! @lab{9’}I resisted but now I attend to those orders (without sleep) at night or during the midday siesta! 

@(B  10’) Apilaša, from childhood, has been loyal to me. @lab{11’}@i{And when he became a (grown) man}, I recognized him in my heart, and once it was clear to you, @lab{12’}my king, with divine insight, you recognized that person, @lab{13’}and promoted him above all the (other) high officials in the foreign territories. @lab{14’}My king, you surpass all great deeds, you [take revenge] on my opponents. @lab{15’ }Give a command; change it!^7^ Your orders are imperative orders; your deeds are great deeds! @lab{16’}(Apilaša’s) supplications are in your heart, daily they are. @lab{17’}He is the mortal who has found favor in your eyes, @lab{18’}so how could I ever be set against him?

#note: ^7^  Var.: Give commands!

@(B  19’)  I have secured the foundations of the frontier and made obedient (all of its inhabitants). @lab{20’}No king can rival my king!  May your heart be glad!

## sjt: my copy had a ref to line 21' at 'May your...' -- but the translit ends at 20'.
