@translation labeled en project
@h1 IbIš1A

@(1) Speak to [Išbi-Erra], @lab{2}s[aying (the words of) Ibbi-Sin, your king]:

(ca. 5 lines missing) 

@(1’) (Now) Enlil’s heart(?) is angry ...

@(2’) The enemy, although not ..., has mustered (his army), and has [brought disorder] in all the foreign lands. @lab{4’}But then you, according to your statement, had an omen @lab{3’}(telling you that) now Enlil [has returned] to the side of his son Sin. 

@(5’) You (text: he) received twenty talents of silver to purchase grain. @lab{6’}You (text: he) purchased grain at the price of two gur per shekel, @lab{7’}to return it to me^5^ as if (you had purchased it) at one gur (per shekel)!

#note: ^5^  Alt. transl.: return it to me.

@(8’) The hostile Amorite, having stationed himself in the frontier territory, @lab{9’}having come to know the strength of my homeland and its troops—@lab{10’}how could you let them sweep into my frontier zone and capture all my large fortresses? @lab{11’ - 12’}Why has Puzur-Marduk, general of Badigihursaŋa, not confronted the Amorites? @lab{13’}Your powerful forces were never brought into play, @lab{14’}it is because of your self-confidence the monkey has [@i{been allowed to come down}] from its mountain!

@(15’) Now I am overhauling 180 great barges, each (vessel) with a capacity of 120 gur, as well as overhauling 600 barges with a capacity of 60 gur each. @lab{17’}Šu-Enlil, governor of Kiš, @lab{18’}Nur-Ea (i.e., Nur-ahum), governor of Ešnunna, @lab{19’}(and) Puzur-Tutu, governor of Borsippa @lab{20’}have handed over 72,000 gur of grain to you, @lab{21’ - 22’}and therefore you should measure out the silver that you have as well @i{as what (was set aside for even) the most exalted allotments} to pay for the 72,000 (gur) of grain. @lab{23’}Do not dare to come back here until you have dispatched (the grain) to me! @lab{24’}Guarding Nippur and Isin is your responsibility. It is urgent!

@h1 IbIš1B

@(X2:1) Speak to Išbi-Erra, @lab{2}saying (the words of) Ibbi-Sin, your king:

@(X2:4) You tell me so: @lab{3}“as long as Enlil is my master, where else (in the world but with you) would I go?” @lab{5}Right now Enlil is angry with me, @lab{6}angry with his son Sin, @lab{7}and is handing over Ur to the enemy. @lab{8}The enemy, although not (yet) within it, has mustered (his army), and created disorder in all the foreign lands. @lab{10}But you, according to your statement, had an omen @lab{9}that Enlil has reconciled with his son Sin. 

@(X2:11) You received twenty talents of silver to purchase grain. @lab{12}You purchased grain at the price of two gur per shekel, @lab{13}but you then returned it to me (as if you had purchased it) at one gur (per shekel). 

@(X2:14) How could you, together with Puzur-Numušda, general of Bad-Igihursaŋa, @lab{15}allow the enemy Amorites to enter into my homeland? @lab{16}Until he returns to you to fight (them) @lab{17}there will be idiots (running around) in the homeland—@lab{18}why has he not confronted the Amorites? 


