@translation labeled en project
@(1) Speak to Ibbi-Sin, my king, @lab{2}saying (the words of) Puzur-Numušda, governor of Kazallu, your servant:

@(3) The envoy of Išbi-Erra came before me (and said): @lab{4}“My king Išbi-Erra, has sent me to you to you with a message.” @lab{5}He presented the matter as follows: @lab{6}“My master Enlil has promised me stewardship of the homeland. @lab{13}Yes, it was me that Enlil ordered @lab{10}to deliver to Ninisina @lab{7}the banks of the Tigris and Euphrates, the Abgal and Me-Enlila canals, @lab{8}their cities, their (city) gods and their armies, @lab{9}from the territory of Hamazi to the Magan Sea, @lab{11}and having made Isin the storehouse of Enlil, made it famous,^4^ @lab{12}to (then) settle their war captives in all those cities.

#note: ^4^  Alt. transl.: Isin, which has to be made the storehouse of Enlil and which has to be made famous.


@(14) Why do you oppose me? @lab{15}I have sworn by my personal god Dagan^5^ @lab{16}that I shall conquer Kazallu! @lab{17}Because Enlil has promised me the cities of the territory, @lab{18}I shall build all their (i.e. the city gods) shrines in Isin, @lab{19}I shall celebrate their regular festivals; @lab{20 - 21}I shall set up my own statues, my own emblems, (choose by omen) my own high priests, chief priests, and high priestesses in their special abodes, @lab{24}so that my subjects may offer their prayers, @lab{22}before Enlil in the Ekur (in Nippur) @lab{23}and before Nanna in the Ekišnuŋal (in Ur). @lab{25 - 26}And as for you, I shall chase out the person you depend on (-Ibbi-Sin){ }from his territory! @lab{27}Isin's wall I shall rebuild @lab{28}(and) name it Idil-pašunu.”

#note: ^5^  Var. I have­ sworn by the name of Enlil, my lord, and of Dagan, my personal god.


@(29) It was just as he had predicted: @lab{30}He rebuilt Isin’s wall @lab{31}(and) named it Idil-pašunu; @lab{32}he took over Nippur, appointed his own guard over it, @lab{33}and arrested Niŋ-dugani, the chief temple administrator of Nippur. @lab{34}(His ally), the ruler/governor Zinnum, took prisoners in Subir @lab{35}(and) plundered Hamazi.^6^ @lab{36}Nur-aḫum, the governor of Ešnunna, @lab{37}Šu-Enlil, the governor of Kiš, @lab{38}and Puzur-Tutu, the governor of Borsippa@lab{39}@i{came over to his side.} @lab{40}His clamor shakes the frontier territory like a reed fence,^7^ @lab{41}as Išbi-Erra goes everywhere at the head of the troops. 

#note: ^6^  Var. ... ­captured Niŋ-dugani, the chief temple administrator of Nippur, and plundered Hamazi. (His ally)­, the ruler/governor Zinnum, took prisoners in Subir.

#note: ^7^  Var. The frontier territory trembles like a reed fence from his clamor.


@(42) It was just as he had predicted: @lab{43}he captured the banks of the Tigris, the banks of the Euphrates, as well as the banks of the Abgal and Me-Enlila. @lab{44}He installed Idi in Malgium,^8^

#note: ^8^ Alt. transl.: He installed Iddin-Malgium.

@(45 - 46) and when Girbubu, governor of Girkal, resisted him and cut off his (Iddi’s) shield, he (Išbi-Erra) took him prisoner. @lab{47}His- clamor has become louder, @lab{48}(and now) he has turned his attention in my direction. @lab{49}I have no ally, no one who can match him! @lab{50}Although he has not yet been able to defeat me, @lab{51}when he finally strikes, I will have to flee! Now my king is informed (about all of this)! 


